	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Disch</b> [ Sat Mar 05, 2005 9:47 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />it'd be easiest to keep each entry in your table's size a power of 2 value -- 2, 4, 8, 16, 32 bytes, etc.  This way you can do quick bitshifting to get the proper index.  To add on to your previous example.... pad each entry of the table to 8 bytes:
<br />
<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">fish_data:<br />db $01 $01 $FF $25 $00 $00&nbsp; &nbsp; $00 $00&nbsp; ; Fish 1's data<br />db $02 $02 $80 $xx $xx $xx&nbsp; &nbsp; $xx $xx&nbsp; ; Fish 2's data<br />; rest of fish data<br /><br /><br /><br />load_fish_data:<br /><br />; get the ID of the fish whose data you want to load<br />LDA fish_id&nbsp; &nbsp; ; 0 would load fish1's data, 1 would load fish 2's, etc<br /><br />; multiply by 8 &#40;8 bytes per fish&#41;<br />ASL A<br />ASL A<br />ASL A<br /><br />; move it to an index reg<br />TAX<br /><br />; Load from your table<br />LDA fish_data, X<br />STA fish_w_data<br /><br />LDA fish_data+1,X<br />STA fish_h_data<br /><br />LDA fish_data+2,X<br />STA fish_y_data<br /><br />;etc<br /><br />RTS<br /><br /></div>
<br />
<br />Also note I changed fish1's Y position to $FF instead of $100 (since $100 can't be represented in a byte -- it would either be truncated to $00, or it would distort your table)

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


